hints_latex:
Since

\begin{align*}
F(x) = \int_0^x p(s)\,ds
\end{align*}

the Fundamental theorem of calculus says that

\begin{align*}
F'(x) = p(x).
\end{align*}

Hence you are asked to plot the derivative of the given function
\emph{F(x)}.

sols_latex:
The derivative \emph{p(x)} is zero whenever \emph{F(x)} is flat, and
\emph{p(x)} is positive whenever \emph{F(x)} is increasing.

